  "prompt": "What are the differences between supermarket and hypermarket?",
  "response": "Here are the key differences between supermarkets and hypermarkets:\n\nSupermarket:\n1. Smaller in size (typically 1,000-2,500 sq. meters)\n2. Focus primarily on food and grocery items\n3. Limited non-food product selection\n4. Standard checkout lanes\n5. Usually located in urban or residential areas\n6. Lower operational costs\n7. Quicker shopping experience\n8. More convenient for daily/weekly shopping\n\nHypermarket:\n1. Much larger in size (typically 5,000-10,000 sq. meters)\n2. Extensive product range including food, electronics, clothing, home goods\n3. Wide variety of non-food products\n4. Multiple checkout areas and services\n5. Often located in suburban areas with large parking spaces\n6. Higher operational costs\n7. Longer shopping time required\n8. One-stop shopping destination\n9. Often includes additional services like pharmacies, banks, restaurants\n10. Usually part of large retail chains\n11. Typically offer bulk purchasing options\n12. More competitive pricing due to large-scale operations\n\nThe main difference is that hypermarkets offer a more comprehensive shopping experience with a broader range of products compared to traditional supermarkets.",
